By default, z3 takes the qffp_tactic. It first reduces the floating point constraint to a bit-vector constraint, which is then eagerly bit-blasted (or "flattened") to an SAT constraint.  It is possible that a "simple" floating point constraint might be translated to a complex SAT formula.

There also exist other tactics in Z3 that can solve floating point constraints which might be better.  For your query, the smt_tactic is very fast.
 ~~~~
// Z3 C++ API
   context ctx;
   solver s = tactic(ctx, "smt").mk_solver(); 
 ~~~~
In general, it is hard to tell which tactic will be the best for a given query.

